 has lagged behind recent GHC releases. Check its compatibility before adopting.\n\n2. **Weeder** (`ocharles/weeder`) -- Detects dead/unused code across a project by analyzing GHC's HIR files. This is not a linter per se, but it fills a gap that HLint does not cover. It has seen active maintenance and is useful for keeping codebases clean.\n\n3. **GHC warnings themselves** -- GHC's built-in warning system has grown increasingly powerful. Using `-Wall -Wextra` (or even `-Werror`) catches many issues. Key flags include:\n   - `-Wunused-binds`, `-Wunused-imports`\n   - `-Wincomplete-patterns`\n   - `-Wmissing-signatures`\n   - `-Wredundant-constraints`\n   - `-Wpartial-fields` (GHC 9.x+)\n   \n   Many developers argue that GHC's warnings have become good enough that they handle a significant portion of what a linter would do.\n\n4. **Fourmolu / Ormolu** -- These are formatters, not linters, but they enforce consistent style and eliminate entire categories of style-related lint. Fourmolu (a more configurable fork of Ormolu) has gained significant traction. Using an auto-formatter means you can turn off many HLint style suggestions and focus HLint on semantic improvements only.\n\n5. **HLS (Haskell Language Server)** -- Integrates HLint directly as a plugin, providing inline suggestions in your editor. This has become the standard way most developers interact with HLint day-to-day, rather than running it as a standalone CLI tool.\n\n6. **Calligraphy** -- A newer tool for visualizing module dependencies. Not a linter, but useful for architectural analysis.\n\n### What About Newer Entrants?\n\nThere have been no major new Haskell linters that have gained significant community adoption in the 2024-2025 timeframe. The Haskell ecosystem is relatively stable in this regard. The trend has been toward:\n\n- Better GHC warnings (each GHC release adds more)\n- Better HLS integration (making HLint more seamless)\n- Auto-formatters reducing the need for style linting\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation\n\nHere is what I would recommend as a **best-practice Haskell linting setup** for a project in 2025-2026:\n\n### Tier 1: Essential (use these)\n\n| Tool | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| **HLint** | Semantic linting, code simplification, idiom enforcement |\n| **GHC `-Wall -Wextra`** | Compiler-level warnings for unused code, incomplete patterns, missing signatures |\n| **Fourmolu** (or Ormolu) | Auto-formatting to eliminate style debates entirely |\n\n### Tier 2: Recommended (add if your project is non-trivial)\n\n| Tool | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| **Weeder** | Dead code detection across the project |\n| **HLS** | Editor integration that surfaces HLint + GHC warnings inline |\n\n### Tier 3: Optional (evaluate for your needs)\n\n| Tool | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| **Stan** | Deeper static analysis (check GHC version compatibility first) |\n| **Custom HLint rules** | Project-specific lint rules via `.hlint.yaml` |\n\n### Configuration Tips\n\n- In `.hlint.yaml`, consider disabling style hints that conflict with your formatter, and focus HLint on its semantic strengths (redundant brackets, eta reduction, map/fmap usage, etc.).\n- Use `{- HLINT ignore -}` pragmas sparingly and only with justification.\n- In CI, run `hlint .` and `fourmolu --mode check .` as blocking checks.\n- Consider `-Werror` in CI but not in development (to avoid friction).\n\n### Bottom Line\n\n**HLint is still the standard and there is nothing that replaces it.** The real evolution in Haskell linting has been in the ecosystem around it: better GHC warnings, formatter adoption, and HLS integration. The best practice is not to pick one tool but to layer them: GHC warnings for correctness, HLint for idioms and simplification, a formatter for style, and Weeder for dead code.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>2906</total_tokens><tool_uses>4</tool_uses><duration_ms>50751</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-jo