binding of the same name from the enclosing scope. An explicit `Solution { assignments = assignments, sums = sums }` would be more robust.\n\n## Test Suite Issues\n\n### 8. Test suite only tests `padInput`, not `solve`\n\n**File:** `/Users/johnw/src/three-partition/test/Spec.hs`\n\nThe test suite only exercises `padInput`. There are no tests for `solve`, which is the core function. Granted, `solve` is an IO action calling an SMT solver (Z3), making it harder to test, but at minimum a smoke test with a known-solvable input would be valuable. The test file does not import `solve`.\n\n### 9. Test suite should compile cleanly\n\nThe test file uses `hspec`, `Test.Hspec.QuickCheck.prop`, and `QuickCheck` (for the `[Int]` type annotation in properties). The `package.yaml` lists both `hspec` and `QuickCheck` as test dependencies. This should compile fine, assuming the library compiles (which it currently does not due to issues 1 and 2).\n\n## Benchmark Issues\n\n### 10. Benchmark only tests `padInput`\n\n**File:** `/Users/johnw/src/three-partition/bench/Main.hs`\n\nSame as the test suite -- only `padInput` is benchmarked. `padInput` is a trivial O(n) function, so benchmarking it provides limited value. Benchmarking `solve` with various input sizes would be more informative (though SMT solver benchmarks can be noisy).\n\n## package.yaml Issues\n\n### 11. No upper bounds on dependencies\n\n**File:** `/Users/johnw/src/three-partition/package.yaml`\n\nAll dependencies use only lower bounds (e.g., `base >= 4.6`). The `sbv` dependency has no version bounds at all, yet the code was written for an older SBV API where `SatModel` was exported from `Data.SBV`. Adding `sbv >= X && < Y` would prevent breakage from API changes like the one that caused issue 1.\n\n### 12. `base >= 4.6` is very permissive\n\n`base >= 4.6` corresponds to GHC 7.6, but the code uses features and extensions that require much newer GHC versions (e.g., `ScopedTypeVariables` with pattern-level type annotations re